1. Rationale

Considering my background in marketing and communications,I have decided to add to the conference database the feature that supports
one of the main purposes of conferences: NETWORKING .

Professional relationships often grow through shared interests and mutual contacts, so I proposed a networking menu that recommends
connections through the friend-of-a-friend who are not directly connected, by up to 4 levels.

Using Neo4j graph relationships, this innovation acts as a simple recommendation engine, and it shows how the database can be used
to store connections, as well as generate meaningful networking opportunities for conference attendees.


2. How It Works

When the user selects the Networking option (Option 7) from the main menu, they are prompted to:

2.1 Enter an attendee ID
2.2 Choose the degree of separation to search (between 2 and 4)

The system then performs a graph traversal on the Neo4j database to identify attendees within the selected number of connections. Direct connections and the attendee themselves are excluded to ensure only new networking opportunities are suggested.

The results display:

 * Suggested attendees
 * Degree of separation
 * Additional attendee details retrieved from the MySQL database

Suggestions can also be ranked based on the number of mutual connections. A Neo4j graph visualisation can be used to display the attendee’s network and highlight recommended connections.


3. Technical Implementation

This feature is implemented using Neo4j and follows best practices in application design.


4. Packages Required

No additional packages are required beyond those already used in the project. All dependencies can be installed with:

pip install neo4j mysql-connector-python python-dotenv


5. Testing on the VM

Step 1 — Run the application
Step 2 — Select option 7 (Networking)
Step 3 — Enter test values [add a few test options/ visuals]
Step 4 — Verify in Neo4j Browser